
Your current diagram appears to be using an older version of React Flow (very likely v9 or earlier, from around 2021–2022), because:

The package was originally called react-flow-renderer
The main component was <ReactFlowRenderer /> (or similar)
The styling looks like the very first generations (colored badges, thick connecting lines, no modern handles, etc.)
No modern features like useNodesState, MiniMap in that style, built-in dark mode support, SSR, etc.
As of March 2026 the current version is React Flow 12 (specifically something like 12.10.x), and the package has been renamed to @xyflow/react.

To upgrade and get a much cleaner, more modern, performant look (better handles, smoother interactions, Tailwind support option, better accessibility, SSR/SSG support, etc.), follow these steps:

1. Install the new package
Remove the old one and install the current version:

# remove old packages
npm uninstall reactflow react-flow-renderer

# install current version (as of 2026)
npm install @xyflow/react
# or with yarn / pnpm / bun accordingly
2. Update your imports (biggest breaking change)
Old (v9 / react-flow-renderer era):

import ReactFlow from 'react-flow-renderer';
New (v12):

import { ReactFlow, useNodesState, useEdgesState, Background, Controls, MiniMap } from '@xyflow/react';

// also import css (important!)
import '@xyflow/react/dist/style.css';
3. Update component usage
Old style (very approximate from your screenshot):

<ReactFlow elements={elements} />
Modern style (recommended – controlled):

import { useCallback } from 'react';
import { ReactFlow, applyNodeChanges, applyEdgeChanges, addEdge, Background, Controls } from '@xyflow/react';
import '@xyflow/react/dist/style.css';

function Flow() {
  const [nodes, setNodes, onNodesChange] = useNodesState(initialNodes);
  const [edges, setEdges, onEdgesChange] = useEdgesState(initialEdges);

  const onConnect = useCallback(
    (params) => setEdges((eds) => addEdge(params, eds)),
    [setEdges],
  );

  return (
    <div style={{ width: '100%', height: '100vh' }}>
      <ReactFlow
        nodes={nodes}
        edges={edges}
        onNodesChange={onNodesChange}
        onEdgesChange={onEdgesChange}
        onConnect={onConnect}
        fitView
      >
        <Background />
        <Controls />
        {/* <MiniMap /> */} {/* optional */}
      </ReactFlow>
    </div>
  );
}
elements → split into nodes + edges arrays
Use state hooks: useNodesState / useEdgesState
Add onConnect if you want drag-to-connect
4. Node / Edge changes you will probably need
Very common breaking renames / adjustments from old → v12:

Old (≈v9)	New (v11 → v12)	Notes
source / target	same	—
parentNode	parentId	very common rename
node data	still data, but don't put logic props directly on node	prefer node.data.xxx
custom node types	same, but use NodeProps type	much better TS support
edgeType	type on edge	—
5. Styling upgrade (recommended)
The old colored look is gone by default. Modern React Flow uses a clean neutral style + you can:

Use Tailwind (many people do this in 2025–2026)
Customize with CSS variables (see docs)
Or bring back something similar with custom node/edge styles
Example minimal Tailwind + modern nodes:

/* in your global css or tailwind */
.react-flow__node {
  @apply border border-gray-300 rounded-lg bg-white shadow-sm;
}

.react-flow__handle {
  @apply w-3 h-3 bg-blue-500 border-2 border-white;
}
Quick upgrade plan summary (2026 edition)
Upgrade React to ≥18 (ideally 19 if your app supports it)
npm install @xyflow/react
Import style + new named imports
Split elements → nodes + edges
Use useNodesState / useEdgesState
Fix parentNode → parentId
Add <Background />, <Controls /> for polish
Test connections / drag / zoom
Customize nodes to look better (rounded, shadows, better handles)
